<TEXT>
bluecollar workers at deere amp co plants in 
five states overwhelmingly ratified a new contract with their first 
general pay raise since 1981 united auto workers officials said 
sunday 
the threeyear pact won 90 percent approval in a vote saturday 
and sunday at deere facilities in illinois iowa atlanta 
minneapolis and denver the unions secretarytreasurer bill 
casstevens said 
the union does not reveal the actual vote on contract 
ratifications spokesman karl mantyla said 
the agreement approved by negotiators representing 13500 
factory workers takes effect immediately 
obviously were very pleased to have a new threeyear labor 
agreement with the uaw said robert combs a spokesman for deere 
it addresses key areas of importance to both of us he said 
citing operational efficiency training job security and 
compensation 
its an agreement we can live with and work with he said 
the contract give deere workers an average pay raise of 443 
cents an hour in the first year followed by lumpsum payments 
equal to 3 percent of their base salary in each of the second and 
third years of the pact 
union workers at deere the nations leading manufacturer of 
farm machinery have earned an average 1547 per hour 
deeres union workforce had not received a general pay raise 
since 1981 the company has given only costofliving increases 
using a formula tied to the consumer price index 
the contract calls for a threestep increase in early retirement 
benefits 
the union also won important safeguards protecting workers from 
layoffs the contract guarantees jobs for all workers employed at 
the time the pact was ratified 
deere is only able to lay off the remainder of its current 
employees in times of high inventories labor disputes plant 
closings sale of a division of the company or an act of god 
company and union representatives negotiated daily for nearly 
two months before a climactic 20hour session that ended with 
approval of the contract proposal 
deere and union officials had negotiated furiously to avoid a 
repeat of the bitter fivemonth strike in 198687 that ended after 
163 days with employees accepting a wage freeze and other 
concessions 
the union plans to soon resume contract negotiations with 
caterpillar inc the uaw has been meeting with negotiators for 
peoriabased caterpillar for two months at a site in bridgeton 
mo near st louis 
caterpillar the worlds leading manufacturer of earthmoving 
equipment and the union agreed to extend its contract originally 
set to expire sept 30 until the deere talks were completed the 
caterpillar contract affects 17500 factory workers in five states 
</TEXT>
