british experts have used a 2684yearold skull 
to reconstruct the head of king midas who according to legend 
turned everything he touched turned into gold the sunday times 
reported 
dr john prag an archaeologist at the manchester museum and 
richard neave an illustrator in the department of medicine at 
manchester university used the latest knowledge about distribution 
of skin tissue on bone to produce the plaster and clay head the 
newspaper said 
midas ruled phrygia in what is now central turkey from 738 bc 
until 696 bc and was considered the most important member of the 
phrygian dynasty 
according to mythology dionysius the god of wine granted 
midas the golden touch and the kings food and even his daughter 
turned to gold he overcame the curse by bathing in a river the 
legend was apparently inspired by midas great wealth 
in 1957 american archaeologists found what was believed to be 
midas tomb in turkey the skeleton was lost the sunday times 
said but last month turkey invited prag and neave to make a 
plaster cast of the skull and attempt the kind of reconstruction 
they made in 1983 of the head of king philip ii of macedonia 
father of alexander the great 
the two experts drilled tiny holes in the plaster cast inserted 
matchsticks at strategic points and smoothed on clay to the 
appropriate thicknesses the newspaper said 
photos accompanying the times story showed a long narrow face 
with a sharply hooked nose small deepset eyes a downturned mouth 
and prominent lower lip 
neave was quoted as saying that the striking feature of midas 
head was that it was deliberately elongated by bandaging in 
childhood because long distorted heads were considered attractive 
at the time 
dr ellen kohler one of the american archaeologists who 
discoverered the tomb in 1957 was thrilled when shown a photo of 
the reconstruction the newspaper said 
the face is quite striking she was quoted as saying in 
philadelphia it fits in with the one terracotta figure of him 
that exists 
she was quoted as saying the now missing skeleton was of a man 5 
feet 3 inches tall who had died at the age 65 
legend also has it that apollo god of music gave midas an ass 
ears after midas judged a music contest between apollo and pan the 
god of fields and forests and found in favor of pan 
the sunday times quoted prag as saying that if midas suffered 
from a malformation of the ear cartilage called darwins tubercle 
it might explain the legend 
we are pursuing it from a medical point of view and our 
colleagues in turkey are going to get in touch with anthropologists 
and geneticists to see if the condition is still prevalent in 
central turkey the newspaper quoted prag as saying 
the times said midas is believed to have been killed or have 
committed suicide when his kingdom was devastated by a barbarian 
tribe called the cimmerians and some argue he would therefore not 
have been given the rich sort of burial indicated by findings at 
the tomb 
professor rodney young who led the american expedition thought 
the tomb was of midas predecessor king gordios the newspaper 
said but today most experts including other members of the team 
believe it was that of midas it said 
