<TEXT>
two out of three small investors who 
experienced problems during the stock market crash are still 
waiting a year later for their complaints to be resolved according 
to a survey released sunday by state regulators 
the north american securities administrators administration said 
64 percent of investors responding to a survey said their problems 
arising from the collapse of the stock market in october 1987 had 
not been resolved 
this confirms our suspicions that small investors were and 
remain the invisible victims of the oct 19 stock market crash 
said john baldwin the new president of the nasaa the national 
organization for state securities regulators 
a full year after black monday those of us who regulate the 
markets at the grass roots level are still finding a surprising 
number of dazed investors stumbling through the ruins of their 
postcrash finances said baldwin who is director of the utah 
securities division 
baldwin said the organizations survey showed that investors who 
had been burned were not rushing back into the market one out of 
seven small investors said they had bailed out of the market 
altogether or were holding less than 500 in securities 
of those still in the market twothirds indicated they had 
changed or were planning to change brokerage firms 
the most common complaint made by half of the survey 
respondents concerned problems with brokers executing trades late 
or getting trades wrong during the hectic period surrounding the 
crash the next most common gripe made by 337 percent of those in 
the survey concerned charges that their broker had misled them 
close behind at 303 percent were complaints concerning brokers 
who put their customers in unsuitable investments such as a highly 
risky venture for a customer without a lot of money to lose 
asked how long it had taken to resolve their complaints an 
overwhelming 64 percent of those responding said their complaints 
were still not resolved some 36 percent said their problem had 
been resolved in one month or less 
among the comments made in the survey 
a housewife in florham park nj who lost 50000 invested 
in stocks wrote my financial security has been drastically and 
unnecessarily destroyed even if i were in a financial position to 
invest now i would never put my money anywhere but in the bank i 
could never have faith in brokers again 
a pineville ala engineer who lost a 197000 portfolio 
accumulated in 20 years of investing wrote since the stock 
market crash i have been surviving day by day depressed trying to 
forget about the stock market 
a retiree in cape gable fla who complained that his broker 
had never outlined the danger of option trading said i lost 
basically everything we owned we have now had to go back to work 
to earn enough to live own 
a new york city public relations man wrote this continues 
to be one of the most painful situations ive ever experienced to 
have lost so much money which was hardearned and difficult to 
