brokerage house that his order placed on oct 20 1987 had been 
mishandled received a credit for more than 6500 covering the 
full amount of his loss 
baldwin said it was important for investors to know what avenues 
of help existed for them to get their complaints resolved he said 
one of the best places to look for assistance was the investors 
state securities bureau 
baldwin said often state regulators were able to get results 
just by getting the brokerage firm and the investor together to 
discuss the problem 
he said arbitration and court suits were also available 
although the survey found that both approaches were time consuming 
of the cases that went to court 90 percent of them were still 
pending and 87 percent of the cases in arbitration were still 
unresolved 
the survey was based on responses to questionnaires mailed to 
2500 callers selected at random from 15000 investors who have 
used a hotline set up following the crash by the nasaa a total of 
829 investors returned the mailed surveys 
the association said the typical respondent was a male aged 55 
or older with a gross income of around 30000 who had lost 
between 1000 and 5000 in the stock market crash 
the survey results were released at the start of the 
associations annual convention in sante fe nm 
