a newspaper on sunday accused officials in a 
central russian city of failing to report the true extent of 
devastation in a train crash and explosion that killed at least 
four people last week 
komsomolskaya pravda the newspaper of the young communist 
league also said there were similarities between the sverdlovsk 
accident and another train accident that killed about 100 people in 
june 
it called for an investigation by the local prosecutor implying 
that criminal negligence or sabotage might be involved 
in these revealing days mixed with human grief are a lack of 
coordination shirking responsibility confusion and unconcealed 
red tape the newspaper said 
on tuesday two freight cars loaded with explosives broke loose 
and smashed into a coal train adjacent to an oil tank yard in 
sverdlovsk a city 850 miles east of moscow 
the resulting double explosion killed at least four people 
according to initial reports and blew a crater 30 feet deep and 
180 feet wide komsomolskaya pravda said its reporter found that at 
least five people died 
in arzamas 240 miles east of moscow a train carrying 
explosives blew up june 4 the newspaper said that train was just 
three minutes away from an oil tank yard 
why do trains full of dangerous materials keep blowing up near 
oil storage areas it asked 
the newspaper said sverdlovsk officials had no idea of the 
extent of the tragedy and didnt know anything about the victims 
except their last names 
the newspaper said its reporter discovered 838 people sought 
medical care and that 10 were in critical condition five lost 
their eyesight the report said 
initial reports said 280 people sought medical care 
authorities in sverdlovsk originally reported 12 dwellings and 8 
other buildings destroyed but the newspaper said 20 apartment 
buildings were destroyed and 14 damaged 
the article said there was no evidence a law requiring that the 
explosives be guarded by four people was observed 
soviet officials have suppressed information on accidents for 
decades and newspapers have only recently begun covering them 
under soviet leader mikhail s gorbachevs policy of glasnost or 
openness 
but even under glasnost some disasters have been hushed up 
when a fire and explosion rocked the chernobyl nuclear power 
station on april 26 1986 soviet authorities denied the accident 
for days and were forced into acknowledging it only after radiation 
contamination was discovered hundreds of miles away in western 
europe the accident killed 31 people 
