<TEXT>
the walt disney world theme park could 
face thousands of dollars in fines for polluting a creek with its 
sewage treatment environmental protection agency officials said 
theyve had violations ongoing for quite some time said 
peter mcgarry who heads the epas water management compliance unit 
for florida fines certainly are a possibility 
for years treated wastewater dumped by disney into reedy creek 
often has carried more phosphorus than allowed by epa and 
sometimes there hasnt been enough oxygen mcgarry said the creek 
flows into lake russell about 10 miles south of kissimmee 
but since disney started using a new artificial wetlands system 
this summer to help clean its wastewater levels of phosphorus and 
nitrogen have doubled or tripled those allowed by epa thats the 
worst problem mcgarry said 
disneys sewage plant now dumps an average of 5 million gallons 
of treated effluent daily into reedy creek said tom moses 
director of disneys reedy creek improvement district 
moses said he plans to ask the kissimmee city commission for 
help the orlando sentinel reported sunday 
kissimmee is allowed to dump into reedy creek more treated 
wastewater and nutrients such as phosphorus than disney but the 
city decided several years ago to build artificial ponds instead of 
dumping into the creek 
moses wants kissimmee to lend disney the right to dump more 
phosphorus and other nutrients into reedy creek for as long as four 
years 
disney could use that time to build new treatment facilities 
improve oxygen levels in the water and see if its 130acre 
artificial wetlands will start working as expected moses said 
disneys problems with epa come about six months after the state 
accused the company of creating a major potential for harm to 
human health and the environment 
in march the state found seven major violations involving 
spilled or leaked hazardous waste the department of environmental 
regulation later fined the company 150299 the largest penalty 
ever imposed by the agencys eightcounty central florida district 
disney has since begun a cleanup effort 
mcgarry said epas decision on whether to impose fines might 
depend on what disney officials after meeting with kissimmee say 
theyll do to clean their wastewater 
epa administrative fines cant exceed 125000 but epa could 
ask the justice department to seek fines of as much as 25000 a 
day he said 
if kissimmee commissioners dont help disney moses said the 
park could race to build new treatment facilities in a few months 
to meet epa limits 
